            {
                "s2_paper_id": "c53cd93bf35ab4543cb94d85e989835766411fbb",
                "title": "The optics of \u2018Day Zero\u2019 and the role of the state in water security for a township in Cape Town (South Africa)",
                "year": 2021,
                "venue": "Water international",
                "citation_count": 5,
                "reference_count": 65,
                "abstract": "ABSTRACT Cape Town (South Africa) provides a unique setting to critique the myriad forces producing the varied, contextual conditions of water security. In post-apartheid Cape Town, water is considered a constitutional right and all citizens are guaranteed free minimum access. Despite this progress, water security is often fragmented and personalized. This paper examines the perspectives and experiences of residents in Langa township following the \u2018Day Zero\u2019 event of 2018. Embedded in the optics of the crisis we found differentiated dimensions of security more reflective of the apartheid era. Our findings illustrate the need for adaptive water governance to promote water justice.",
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "104777888",
                        "name": "G. LaVanchy"
                    },
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "32336412",
